A Ponzi scheme is a fraudulent investment operation that pays returns to existing investors from funds contributed by new investors, rather than from profit earned. It is named after Charles Ponzi, who became infamous for using this technique in the early 1900s.

To do a Ponzi scheme, a person or organization would typically create an investment opportunity that promises high returns with little to no risk. They would then use money from new investors to pay the returns to earlier investors, rather than using that money to invest in the business or other legitimate activities.

As more and more people invest their money, the Ponzi scheme can continue to grow, providing the appearance of legitimacy and success. However, eventually the number of new investors will slow down, and the Ponzi scheme will collapse when there are not enough new investors to provide the necessary funds to pay the returns to earlier investors.

It is important to note that Ponzi schemes are illegal and can result in severe penalties for those involved.
